  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 16, 17.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The main sins of Israel are now specified, that they themselves may stand self-convicted, and that others may be warned against doing the like. First, generally. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They left all the commandments of the Lord their God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " neglected them, rendered them no obedience, offered none of the stated sacrifices, attended none of the appointed feasts, broke the moral law (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 4:1, 2, 11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) by swearing, and lying, and stealing, and committing adultery, by drunkenness, and lewdness, and bloodshed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And made them molten images, even two calves.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " These at least were undeniable - there they were at Dan and Bethel, until the Captivity came (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 8:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 10:5, 6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 13:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), worshipped, sworn by (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), viewed as living gods (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), offered to, trusted in. Every king had upheld them, so that Bethel was regarded as \"the king's court,\" and \"the king's chapel\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 7:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); all the people were devoted to them, and \"brought their sacrifices to Bethel every morning\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 4:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), \"and their tithes after three years.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And made a grove.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The \"grove \"(",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "asherah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") which Ahab set up at Samaria (1 Kings 16:38), and which remained there certainly to the time of Jehoahaz (see the comment on 2 Kings 13:6). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And worshipped all the host of heaven.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This worship had not been mentioned before; and it is nowhere else ascribed to the Israelites of the northern kingdom. Manasseh seems to have introduced it into Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:5, 11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Such knowledge as we have of the Western Asiatic religions seems to indicate that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "astral",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " worship, strictly so called, was a peculiarity of the Assyro-Babylonian and Arabian systems only, and did not belong to the Syrian, or the Phoenician, or the Canaanite. It may be suspected that the present passage is somewhat rhetorical, and assigns to the Israelites the \"worship of the host of heaven,\" simply because an astral character attached to Baal and Ashtoreth, who were associated in the religion of the Phoenicians with the sun and moon. On the ether hand, it is just possible that the Assyro-Babylonian star-worship had been introduced into Israel under Menahem, Pekah, or Hoshea. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And served Baal.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Baal-worship, introduced by Ahab (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), was not finally abolished by Jehu (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 10:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Like other popular religions, it had a revival Hosea, writing under the later kings from Jeroboam II. to Hoshea, alludes to the Baal-worship (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 2:8, 17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as continuing. 2 Kings 17:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The climax of their apostasy: \"They made themselves molten images, two (golden) calves\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which are called מסּכה after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"and Asherah,\" i.e., idols of Astarte (for the fact, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), \"and worshipped all the host of heaven (sun, moon, and stars), and served Baal\" - in the time of Ahab and his family (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The worshipping of all the host of heaven is not specially mentioned in the history of the kingdom of the ten tribes, but occurs first of all in Judah in the time of Manasseh (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The fact that the host of heaven is mentioned between Asherah and Baal shows that the historian refers to the Baal and Astarte worship, and has borrowed the expression from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to show the character of this worship, since both Baal and Astarte were deities of a sidereal nature. The first half of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rests upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 18:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the worship of Moloch is forbidden along with soothsaying and augury. There is no allusion to this worship in the history of the kingdom of the ten tribes, although it certainly existed in the time of Ahab. The second half of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also refers to the conduct of Ahab (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 21:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]